result.execSummary:
All charges against Rakeem Saleam Taylor in this case have been dismissed. These charges were not proven and have no legal effect. Rakeem Saleam Taylor is presumed innocent.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: Defendant Rakeem Saleam Taylor in court with attorney Michael Jude.  Defendant Rakeem Saleam Taylor in custody.  Thomas Potter for Ronald Dague appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Contested competency hearing proceeded.  Sworn:  Dr. Deborah Collins.  Court finds defendant is incompetent to proceed at this time, but if provided with appropriate medication and treatment, is likely to become competent.  Court also finds the involuntary administration of medication(s) and treatment is needed because the defendant is incapable of expressing an understanding of the advantages and disadvantages of accepting medication or treatment and the alternatives.  Court suspends proceedings.   Defendant has credit for 219 days time served.  Court adjourns matter for Return on Doctor's Report.  Doctor's Report Return scheduled for August 3, 2016 at 01:30 pm.
